ENGLISH.EASSY_DETAILS:
DIRECTIONS for questions 8 and 9: Answer the questions on the basis of the information given below.

For a set, S, of natural numbers, any collection of ordered pairs of the form (a, b), where a S and b S, is said to be a relation, R, defined on S. If for every a S, (a, a) R, then R is said to be a reflexive relation on S. Otherwise it is not reflexive on S. For example, if S = {1, 2, 3, 4}, then R1 = {(1, 1) (2, 2) (3, 3) (4, 4)} and R2 = {(1, 1) (2, 2) (3, 3) (4, 4) (1, 4)} are reflexive on S but R3 = {(1, 1) (2, 2)} is not reflexive on S.
